ce:section.ce:para:
The obtained results (Fig. 2
                           ) revealed that histamine causes the inhibition of the emission intensity of AIS QDs while the intensity of the CDs' emission band remains practically unaffected. This confirmed that in the ratiometric sensing nanoprobe, ternary QDs could be used as analyte-dependent fluorophores (Fig. 3
                           a), as the addition of small concentrations of histamine resulted in a significant PL inhibition, while CDs could be employed as reference fluorophore. Along with the quenching effect on the emission intensity, the MPA-AIS QDs/histamine interaction study also revealed that increasing BA concentrations led to a red shift of the QDs maximum emission wavelength of up to 50 nm (662–712). The observed redshift effect confers an additional selectivity toward the analyte. In fact, there is a panoply of analytes capable of inducing a PL quenching effect on the QDs, but only some can lead to a bathochromic deviation of the QDs’ maximum emission wavelength. This could provide a specific analyte-response profile, which facilitates the analyte discrimination in complex samples when applying the chemometric models to the obtained results (Castro, Ribeiro, & Santos, 2021; Ribeiro et al., 2019).
